text: Why is [[!Balance]] good to the point of being banned?
It’s too cheap for the effect and it doesn’t represent the kind of gameplay they want to encourage.
So the two more mana is fine for Armageddon?
Sure
This gets rid of cards and lands for half the mana.
and creatures
And more importantly, you keep artifacts and enchantments
So you can just play manarocks.dec with Land Tax and enchantments and win, basically.
Or superfriends now too
In monowhite, it might almost be fair. In multicolor, it's not even close.
It's basically turns stax into turbo stax.
[[Balancing Act]], however, is a really great option.

text: The difference between Ward of Bones and Damping Engine is that Damping Engine picks on the guy who is probably archenemy anyway, or at the very least is only picking on one guy.
person*
Ward of Bones unites an entire table against you. Immediately.
And it costs two more for the privilege.

text: Cedric used a walker as a commander! Get ready for a collective shit storm, especially if he wins.
Commander Vs has done that for years.
Josh is using Ral Zarek it seems.
Plus, it’s Brawl.
I won a lot of Type II tournaments (meaning like 12 players) early in Magic by floating mana, saccing all my lands to a Zuran Orb, and casting Balance
It’s so galling to see CZ play Brawl with how much they shit on it.
i'm assuming that some number of their episodes are directly sponsored by wotc, who get some input as to those episode formats?
Of course, but the hypocrisy is so blatant.
They do shit on it pretty hard, but really just the rotation aspect. And you could tell they legitimately had a blast with it when it was on Game Knights.
They don’t really make that distinction when they make snide comments about the format and no one playing it, etc.
I mean... I love Brawl, but they're not wrong. Rotation is a huge hurdle, and no one is playing the format.
Esp on social media
That could change with support (videos, articles, making planeswalker Intro Decks Brawl legal, etc)
But until we see that... It's gonna stay like it is.
rotation is a deal breaker for many people (including me)
It's bad. Like, real bad.
The rotation problem, that is.
granted, the concept of rotation is crucial for wotc's economic survival, so it is understandably shoehorned in
The whole point of Brawl is to be something besides commander. If you want a non-rotating format, that exists.

I'd say that the monetary hit from Brawl is a little overstated too, decks are generally going to cost less than the edh coutnerparts, plus with how often folks take decks apart and rebuild something different, I'd wager it's not that much more different than the length of rotation as well. Pet decks excluded
I don't disagree, henry. I just know from practice that as a guy who is really into Brawl, and has been through just one rotation... It really put a hit on both me and my whole playgroup.
To the point where we just allowed pre-rotation decks, so long as they hadn't been updated.
eternal brawl
Because otherwise we weren't going to be able to play at all.
I'd be curious what the average life of an edh deck is for the crowd who say they don't play brawl because of rotation is, namely the extra vocal naysayers.(Not you Nate)
i'd be down for eternal brawl if it were a recognized thing
Like, does JLK shit on brawl because of rotation but only 2 of his XX personal decks actually last longer than 2 years before he takes it apart.
Does EDH need a Modern equivalent?
nope!
It would just be EDH-lite.
EDH is a modern equivalent
that question has different answers depending on who is asking (hasbro executives)
Pretty much, yeah.
Nonrotating place to play your crads
Standard is the right thing for Brawl, it just needs either more popularity or a way to play older versions of Standard.
The one my playgroup was throwing around for a minute was "one block/two sets from any given set chronologically, backward or forward."
Which is much easier to explain with a chart... which is a problem.
i truly do not care which set a card comes from
which makes many formats silly in my eyes
I mean, that makes sense, from an EDH perspective.
and it makes the brainstorm brewery card guessing games harder

I guess my point is... Wizards holds all the cards when it comes to whether or not Brawl is going to survive. If you've played it, you know that it's a fun, shorter version of EDH that is also cheaper and easier to access from a rules perspective.
But without clear support, it's just not going to survive. I hope we see that this time around, once CZ makes it popular for a week again.
i.e. playable on Arena this month, and followup content/product from wotc.
a set full of planeswalkers is effectively indirect wotc support for a PW-as-commander format
Sure, provided it's followed up by any mention of the format at all.
Which it does seem like we may be getting with CZ.
So... here's hopin'.

If you’ve seen the 1v1 banlist for EDH on MTGO you get a glimpse of how well WotC would manage the list and extrapolate to how well they understand how to manage the format overall. So their implicit support of Walkers doesn’t mean much.
To be fair Henry, there's lots of parts of my job I shit on, but still do them with a smile when paid to.
Sure but you don’t broadcast your shitting to the same audience you later try and smile and say this hit ain’t half bad.
You’re summarizing Cedric Philips whole stance on MTG
That's fair Henry
Brawl is dead in paper. Arena might give it life
My opinion anyway
I think Arena is the only way it'll become established.
There was a thread on reddit awhile back and every comment was "since I can't play EDH on Arena, I'd love to play Brawl there, but I'm never playing it in paper."
